Description.0: 2D array of the Youngs moduli of the materials. Each row represents a material, the three columns represent E11, E22 and E33.

Description.2: 2D array of the Poisson ratio of the materials. Each row represents a material, the three columns represent nu12, nu13 and nu23.

Description.4: 2D array of the Ultimate Compressive Strength (UCS) of the materials. Each row represents a material, the three columns represent Xc12, Xc13 and Xc23.
Description.5: 2D array of the Ultimate Shear Strength (USS) of the materials. Each row represents a material, the three columns represent S12, S13 and S23.
Description.6: Yield stress of the material (in the principle direction for composites).
Description.7: Exponent of S-N Wohler fatigue curve in the form of S = A*N^-(1/m).
Description.8: Stress-intercept (A) of S-N Wohler fatigue curve in the form of S = A*N^-(1/m), taken as ultimate stress unless otherwise specified.

Description.30: 4D array with the moment coefficients of the airfoils. Description.1190: Levelized cost of energy: LCOE is the cost that, if assigned to every unit of electricity by an asset over an evaluation period, will equal the total costs during that same period when discounted to the base year.
Description.1191: Levelized value of energy: LVOE is the discounted sum of total value divided by the discounted sum of electrical energy generated.
Description.1192: Value factor is the LVOE divided by a benchmark price.
Description.1193: Net value of capacity: NVOC is the difference in an asset’s total annualized value and annualized cost, divided by the installed capacity of the asset. NVOC ≥ 0 for economic viability.
Description.1194: Net value of energy: NVOE is the difference between LVOE and LCOE. NVOE ≥ 0 for economic viability.
Description.1195: System LCOE: SLCOE is the negative of NVOE but further adjusted by a benchmark price. System LCOE ≤ benchmark price for economic viability.
Description.1196: Benefit cost ratio: BCR is the discounted sum of total value divided by the discounted sum of total cost. A higher BCR is more competitive. BCR ≥ 1 for economic viability
Description.1197: Cost benefit ratio: CBR is the inverse of BCR. CBR ≤ 1 for economic viability. A lower CBR is more competitive.
Description.1198: Return on investment: ROI can also be expressed as BCR – 1. A higher ROI is more competitive. ROI ≥ 0 for economic viability.
Description.1199: Profit margin: PM can also be expressed as 1 - CBR. A higher PM is more competitive. PM ≥ 0 for economic viability.
Description.1200: Profitability adjusted PLCOE is the product of a benchmark price and CBR, which is equal to LCOE divided by value factor. A lower PLCOE is more competitive. PLCOE ≤ benchmark price for economic viability.
